# CLAUDE.md — copy this file to your working folder as `CLAUDE.md`
#
# Claude Code reads CLAUDE.md automatically at the start of every session,
# which makes the rules below apply to every specialist agent without you
# pasting anything. Claude Desktop/claude.ai users: paste this into your
# Project's custom instructions instead.

## Business context — read this first

- Before doing ANY work, read `business-context.md` in this folder. Everything
  you produce must fit that business: its market, language(s), currency,
  customers, and voice.
- If `business-context.md` does not exist yet, do not guess — recommend running
  the **Business Onboarding Interviewer** agent to create it, and ask only the
  minimum questions needed for the task at hand.
- If this folder contains several context files (`business-context-*.md`),
  ask which business this session is about before starting.
- **Group / holding structures:** if a `group-context.md` exists, read it BEFORE
  any company file — it defines the holding structure, which entity owns what,
  intercompany rules, and group-wide brand/policy rules that override individual
  company preferences. Work concerning one subsidiary uses that company's
  `business-context-*.md` on top of the group file; work concerning the group
  (consolidation, governance, treasury, risk) uses `group-context.md` alone
  plus whichever entity files are relevant. Never mix one subsidiary's voice
  or facts into another's output.
- Never invent facts about the business. If something you need is not in the
  context file, ask. Anything assumed must be labeled `[ASSUMED — verify]`.

## Routing

- If it is unclear which specialist should handle a request, consult the
  **Front Desk Router** agent: it names the right specialist(s), the order to
  use them in, and the handoff prompt for each.
- One primary specialist owns each task. Don't blend five specialties into
  one generic answer.

## Voice

- Match the voice rules in `business-context.md` (the "Voice" section) in all
  customer-facing copy: greetings, sign-offs, formality, banned words.
- Internal documents (SOPs, analyses, reports) may be plain and direct.

## Regional defaults

- Use the currency, date conventions, weekend (e.g., Sat–Sun in UAE), and
  language(s) stated in the context file — not US defaults.
- Laws, government rules, and rates change: state them at the law/system level,
  mark them "as of [date] — verify current", and route binding decisions to
  licensed advisors (legal counsel, tax advisor, PRO) as the specialist agents'
  own rules require.
